<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / ITC chief warns on pursuit of ratings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INDEPENDENT Tele-vision Commission yesterday warned both ITV and Channel
4 not to go too far in the pursuit of ratings at the expense of programme
obligations.
Mr David Glencross, ITC chief executive, said that although the start of the
new ITV licences had gone better than expected there were still areas of
concern. He said viewers of religious programmes were less well-served, and
the scheduling of The South Bank Show, the Sunday arts programme, was edging
closer to 11pm than 10.30pm.
'It will not take much more slippage of this kind for the ITC to question
seriously whether the quality and diversity of the service required by the
1990 (Broadcasting) Act was in fact being met,' he told the annual
conference of the Viewers and Listeners Association in London.
Channel 4 - now winning 11.5 per cent of viewing - was right, he said, to
expand its audience share. He did not believe it had breached its remit to
appeal to tastes not catered for elsewhere.
'But there is a temptation for Channel 4 to go that extra inch for a little
more revenue, a little more audience and I believe at the margins of choice
the competitive instincts of the channel must yield to the sanctity of the
remit,' Mr Glencross warned.
</TEXT>
