<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Inquiry attacks role of BBC governors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN UNOFFICIAL commission of inquiry into the future of the BBC yesterday
criticised the role of the BBC governors.
The commission, chaired by Mr Wilf Stevenson, director of the British Film
Institute, also expressed concern about the BBC's policy of producer choice,
which gives producers the right to buy in services from outside the
corporation.
The commission expressed 'serious worries' that the policy would favour
outsiders bidding at marginal cost over insiders shouldering BBC overheads,
leading to 'a running-down of the BBC'.
The inquiry said it had heard no adequate defence of the role of the BBC
governors, which caused confusion because they were in effect a second layer
of management.
It 'found little confidence in their representativeness, openness or
independence from government'.
The report is to be submitted to the Department of National Heritage in
response to the green paper on the future of the BBC.
The total number of BBC employees in the corporation's top two pay grades
has risen over the past three years while more than 3,000 staff jobs have
been lost, according to BBC figures. In 1990 there were 1,363 people in the
top two grades. By March that had risen to 1,424.
</TEXT>
