<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / TUC region presses for wider balloting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NORTHERN region of TUC is to lobby for the next general secretary to be
elected by a vote of all members of TUC-affiliated unions.
Mr Bob Howard, regional secretary, said the TUC had for too long been seen
as a London-based office, selecting its general secretary and senior
officials on the basis of 'Buggins' turn'.
Stressing that he was not seeking the position, Mr Howard said he was not
against Mr John Monks, deputy general secretary who is expected to succeed
Mr Norman Willis when he takes early retirement.
The ethos of the union movement now, said Mr Howard, was to move towards
'universal democratic membership suffrage'.
Adoption of that in the selection of the general secretary by giving all
members of affiliated unions a personal vote could overcome the 'unfair
criticism' suffered by Mr Willis, he said. 'It would reinforce the authority
of whoever became general secretary.'
The TUC said that no union had asked to change the system. Nominations from
affiliated unions will be open until mid July. If more than one nomination
is made, delegates at the TUC's annual congress in September will vote on
the basis of one vote per 1,000 members they represent.
</TEXT>
