<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Britain's car output up again
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK is poised to become a substantial car production centre again with
output growing faster than in any other part of Europe, Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary (above), said yesterday. Mr
Heseltine was speaking at the opening of Honda's Pounds 300m car assembly
plant at Swindon, Wiltshire. The UK had attracted more than 40 per cent of
all Japanese inward investment into the European Community, and Japanese
investment in car manufacturing in Britain had 'had a major influence on the
revival' of that industry, he said. Honda, the only one of the three
Japanese carmakers in the UK not to recognise a trade union, defended its
policy, saying workers had a 37-hour week and retirement at 60.
</TEXT>
