<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / World Trade News: Belfast-New York air link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK has authorised a scheduled air service between Belfast and New York,
the first for almost a decade.
London wants the granting of the licence to be seen by Mr Federico Pena, the
US transportation secretary, as a positive sign ahead of talks between the
two countries over replacing their bilateral aviation agreement.
Mr John MacGregor, the UK transport secretary, said: 'This is a special
exception given outside the terms of the UK/US aviation agreement.'
The new service - by American Trans Air, a US charter specialist based in
Indianapolis - starts in June with three flights a week.
The UK and the US have given themselves a year to negotiate a new agreement.
