<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Fed backs dollar against rising yen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Reserve intervened on the foreign exchange markets yesterday,
buying dollars for yen, in the clearest indication yet that the Clinton
administration is concerned about the recent appreciation of the Japanese
currency. The Fed intervened in support of the dollar against the yen for
the first time this year after the US currency hit another all-time low of
Y109.15 in New York.
Dealers said there were four rounds of dollar-buying by the Federal Reserve
in New York at levels between Y109.50 and Y110.50. The intervention took
currency dealers by surprise, pushing the dollar up to a London close of
Y111.2.
There was no detailed explanation for the intervention from US officials.
However, Mr Lloyd Bentsen, Treasury Secretary, told a senate subcommittee
hearing that excessive volatility in exchange rates could be
counter-productive.
The US intervention also followed accusations by Japanese officials that the
Clinton administration had been attempting to talk up the Yen in an effort
to reduce Japan's trade surplus with the US.
Mr Bentsen said: 'I think there have been some misconceptions about US
exchange rate policy. I want to underscore the administration's belief that
exchange rates should reflect fundamentals. We are monitoring developments
closely.'
Mr Bentsen was quoted as saying there would be a communique on exchange
rates after a Group of Seven finance ministers meeting tomorrow.
Mr Mark Brett, an economist at Barclays de Zoete Wedd in London, said that
the Clinton administration might now think that the continuing depreciation
of the dollar would have only a limited impact on the trade surplus.
Mr Jim O'Neill of Swiss Banking Corporation, said that the US administration
might have been moved to act by the weakness in both US bond and equity
markets in recent days and by a gold price surge. Currencies, Page 35
</TEXT>
