<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Eritrea celebrates independence vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIE WHEELWRIGHT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ASMARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ERITREANS celebrated in the streets of Asmara last night after provisional
results of the United Nations-monitored referendum gave near unanimous
support for independence from Ethiopia.
International recognition is now a formality. In a 98 per cent turnout of
registered voters, 1.1m voted Yes and only 1,822 voted No, writes Julie
Wheelwright in Asmara.
'Eritrea is a sovereign country as of today, April 27, 1993,' former
Eritrean guerrilla leader Isayas Afewerki and secretary general of the
provisional government told a news conference in the capital.
A formal declaration of independence, achieved after a 30-year war which
cost over 100,000 lives, will be made on May 24 - the second anniversary of
the defeat by Eritrean guerrillas of the army of President Mengistu Haile
Mariam, the former Ethiopian dictator who fled into exile.
