<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Bosnia Conflict: UN concern at flare-up in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERB forces yesterday defied the international community by launching an
attack in Moslem-held north-western Bosnia just as tough new United Nations
sanctions went into force against Belgrade.
Fighting also erupted in other parts of former Yugoslavia, one day after
Bosnian Serbs refused to accept an international peace plan signed by rival
Moslems and Croats.
About 100 Serb troops backed by 10 tanks and artillery advanced several
miles into the area around the north-western town of Bihac early yesterday,
a spokesman for the UN forces said.
UN military observers stationed in the Bihac region reported fighting in
four locations in the area, where 300,000 people are being supplied with aid
by the UN.
The new fighting was sure to anger the international community, which
started applying sanctions against the Serbian-led rump Yugoslavia yesterday
and is considering limited military intervention to halt the year-old civil
war.
In Belgrade, a map showing the locations of bomb shelters in the city was
published by 'popular demand' in Vecernje Novosti, the mass circulation
daily.
Nato chiefs, meeting in Brussels yesterday, focused on a narrowing set of
options ranging from air strikes to the setting up of protected zones.
The top-level committee meeting was attended by General Colin Powell,
chairman of the US joint chiefs of staff.
The allies were awaiting an announcement on a possible visit this week by Mr
Warren Christopher, the US secretary of State, to European capitals. These
were expected to include London, Paris, Bonn, Rome and Moscow.
Mr Christopher, testifying to a senate panel in Washington yesterday, set
rigorous criteria for the use of force by the US.
He said the use of force had to meet four tests: the goal would have to be
stated clearly to the American people; there must be a strong likelihood the
use of force could be successful; there must be an exit strategy; and a
programme that could sustain the support of the American people.
There was a consensus in Brussels that any bombing of military positions or
supply lines would involve some degree of alliance involvement, and it was
made clear that Washington would not obtain backing from allies without
specific authority from the UN.
Nato contingency planning has so far concentrated on formation of a
peacekeeping force which would back up the Vance-Owen peace plan if a
ceasefire were established. But officials said these plans - calling mainly
on US, British, French and Russian troops - had now been 'put on ice'.
Officials said there had been 'reasonably detailed' consideration of
different kinds of safe areas for Bosnian Moslems. The lowest level would
just involve 'relief zones'.
Alternatively safe areas might be set up inside perimeters controlled by UN
troops, but without the forces necessary to withstand heavy attacks.
Another option would be more heavily defended safe havens modelled on the
precedent of northern Iraq.
In Stockholm, Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, said the
options did not exclude lifting the UN embargo on arms shipments to Bosnian
Moslem forces.
However, he said that such a move would require careful consideration before
it could be accepted as 'a wise decision'.
Speaking at a press conference after a two-day visit to Sweden, Mr Hurd said
he did not believe it was possible in practice to lift the arms embargo for
one party only.
A decision to end the embargo, which would require a UN Security Council
resolution, would therefore involve a shift in policy from one of trying to
stop the fighting in Bosnia to allowing the combatants to fight it out to
the finish.
</TEXT>
