<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Congress threatens end to EBRD funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Congress is likely to refuse further money for the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development as a result of the outcry over excessive
spending on salaries, private aircraft and office fittings.
The Clinton administration has requested Dollars 70m (Pounds 45.1m) in its
1994 budget for the US's share of the EBRD's paid-up capital, but senior
members of Congress warned yesterday that they would almost certainly refuse
the request.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, treasury secretary, said he shared Congress's concerns
about the EBRD, calling its spending 'absolutely unacceptable'. He defended
the capital subscription, however, and said the US was insisting on
restructuring of the EBRD's budget process, much tighter oversight and
outside auditing.
As the US issued its warning, Mr Jacques Attali, the bank's chairman,
promised in London to reinforce budgetary controls and introduce greater
transparency. Senator Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the Democratic chairman of
the Senate committee that controls foreign aid spending, said he planned to
reduce the EBRD budget allocation to zero unless very substantial changes in
the bank's management were made.
He said: 'I will not vote for one cent of money from the US for the EBRD
unless I see very, very substantial movements towards reform - not promises
of reform. There will not be one cent in my proposal unless I see that, and
frankly I don't think I am going to.'
Mr Leahy delivered a scathing indictment of the EBRD's spending and of Mr
Attali. 'I want to know why we should entrust another dime of the public's
money to Mr Attali,' he said. 'It's almost like this money that has gone in
there is a slush fund for personal use.'
The US is the largest of the 56 shareholders in the EBRD. It accounts for 10
per cent of the bank's capital.
Republican members are likely to follow the Democrats on the EBRD.
Senator Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, Mr Leahy's Republican counterpart on
the foreign operations spending committee, said: 'Short of immediate changes
in the policies and practices of the EBRD, I - like the chairman - cannot
support the administration's request for Dollars 70m.' Foreign aid remains
one of the least popular areas of the budget in the US Congress. Members
warn that it remains politically impossible to reduce aid to Israel and
Egypt, which receive the lion's share of the US aid budget, but Congress is
warning that Dollars 1.8bn needs to be found to fund the US's recent promise
of new bilateral aid at the Tokyo G7 meeting. The administration has not yet
specified where it wants the money to come from. Mr Leahy said he might not
support the administration's request for Dollars 1.25bn this year for the
International Development Association, a third of the US's contribution to
the tenth replenishment of this concessional loan arm of the World Bank.
Mr Bentsen argued, however, that the money was essentially the same in real
terms as the last contribution, negotiated in 1986.
He added that the US's ability to influence the multilateral development
banks was impaired by its position as the only leading industrialised
country in arrears in its payments to those institutions, to the tune of
Dollars 374m. 'These arrears damage the standing of the US in the
international community,' he said.
Mr Attali, speaking after the bank's annual meeting, said that the bank
would increase its private-sector investment.
He was warned by Ms Anne Wibble, the Swedish finance minister who has taken
over from Mr Theo Waigel of Germany as chairman of the bank's board of
governors, that 'the time for grand designs' was over. 'I would like the
bank to focus on the operational aspects of its activity,' she stressed.
Mr Attali said that after the criticism of the bank, there was now no
question of his quitting until his 'baby' can 'go it alone'.
Attali pressed to get on with main task, Page 2
</TEXT>
