<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Halifax seeks freedom to widen range of products
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALIFAX, Britain's largest building society, says it wants to join the
Personal Investment Authority, the proposed new self-regulatory body for
retail financial services, and to distribute a wider variety of financial
products.
Mr Jim Birrell, Halifax's chief executive, told the Financial Times that he
would like to see a relaxation of the polarisation rules that require
financial services outlets either to sell one supplier's products
exclusively or to offer the best product of each supplier.
Polarisation was introduced under the Financial Services Act to limit some
of the most abused sales practices. However, critics of the measure have
argued that what is needed is not polarisation but better regulation.
Mr Birrell said the PIA was showing signs of becoming an effective
regulator. 'We feel encouraged with the way the PIA is shaping up and we
thought we should say so,' he said.
The future of the PIA has been cloudy because life insurance companies have
said they will not join unless leading banks and building societies do,
while banks and building societies are insisting that tough rules should be
set for independent sales agents. Mr Birrell's remarks thus make the PIA's
success more likely.
Tied agents such as Halifax do not need to belong to any self-regulatory
body. Instead they are regulated indirectly by Lautro, the self-regulatory
body for life insurers, which oversees their insurance-company supplier.
Participation in self-regulatory bodies should give banks and building
societies the influence they deserve to help change the regulatory
structure, Mr Birrell said. 'We would like a seat at the table and the
ability to influence the discussion,' he added.
He made clear that Halifax, which is 'tied' to the life insurer Standard
Life, is hoping for regulatory changes that will allow it to offer a far
wider range of products. 'If you take the Marks and Spencer analogy, you
would deal with a limited number of suppliers for mainline products, but
surely they deal with more than one.'
Mr Birrell said Halifax had no plans to end its tied relationship with
Standard Life. 'But we want to look at our long-term strategy in retail
financial services.'
Among other things, Halifax would like to see the de-polarisation of certain
products, unit trusts in particular, whose pricing structure is more readily
apparent to potential customers.
</TEXT>
