<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Two jailed for oil bids racket
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO OIL industry information brokers were both jailed for three years
yesterday after being convicted of bribing senior employees of British
Petroleum to obtain confidential details of contract bids.
Mr Josef Szrajber and Mr Paulo Sorelli sold information about rival bids to
engineering companies competing for lucrative North Sea oil contracts. Mr
Sorelli obtained the information and Mr Szrajber negotiated and received
customers' payments.
Last month both men were convicted at Southwark Crown Court, London, on
seven counts of conspiring to defraud BP.
Sentencing them yesterday, Judge Valerie Pearlman said: 'You quite
deliberately, as a business, pursued a course of conduct where you obtained
the information about the contents of sealed tenders so you could sell this
information to other companies competing for the award of very lucrative
contracts. What each of you did was strike at the very root of commercial
probity and that has to be treated very seriously indeed.'
They were responsible for helping companies win work worth a total of Pounds
100m. The value of the contracts varied from Pounds 625,000 to Pounds 50m.
Working on a commission basis they received Pounds 1.7m between them.
Mr Szrajber was fined Pounds 407,000 and Mr Sorelli Pounds 429,000 after it
was agreed they had benefited to that extent. Both were ordered to pay
Pounds 65,000 towards prosecution costs.
</TEXT>
