FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Seibu turns in first deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEIBU, the Japanese department store group, announced yesterday that sales
had fallen below those of Mitsukoshi, its main rival, for the first time in
five years, writes Charles Leadbeater in Tokyo.
Seibu, which is privately owned, took the unprecedented step of publishing a
financial report. It announced it had made its first ever pre-tax
unconsolidated loss in the year to end-February. It was the first loss at
the group since its founding in 1940.
The loss was mainly due to a scandal involving medical equipment, which
forced Seibu into an extraordinary loss of Y19.7bn (Dollars 175m).
