<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Intel's shares tumble on price
war fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL'S stock price dropped sharply yesterday, on concerns that the
semiconductor manufacturer will face increasing price competition in the
market for microprocessors used in personal computers.
Intel currently dominates this market but yesterday Motorola, the second
largest manufacturer, announced its entry into the field with the launch of
its first Power PC microprocessor, developed in conjunction with IBM and
Apple Computer. Motorola said that it will price the first Power PC chip at
Dollars 280, for customers ordering 20,000 chips. A faster version will be
priced at Dollars 374.
'Our goal is to make the PowerPC a standard in the computer industry,' said
Motorola.
Prices for Intel's 486 microprocessor, its leading product, range from
Dollars 90 to Dollars 550, depending upon the speed and packaging of the
chip. Next month, Intel is expected to price its new Pentium microprocessor
at about Dollars 900.
Intel's shares dropped by Dollars 5 1/4 to Dollars 87 3/8 yesterday, while
Motorola lost Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 69 1/8 . Advanced Micro Devices also
retreated to Dollars 29 1/4 , down Dollars 1 1/4 .
