FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Polish bank sale oversubscribed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WIELKOPOLSKI Bank Kredytowy, Poland's first state-owned 'high street' bank
to be sold off, has been heavily oversubscribed, according to the finance
ministry.
Mr Slawomir Sikora, the head of the ministry's banking department, said
710bn zlotys (Dollars 42m) had been offered for the 460,000 shares with
total a issue price 52.9bn zlotys.
All foreign and local private sector buyers have been issued shares but only
9.2 per cent of the amount they had applied for.
This issue represents 10 per cent of the existing capital. However, the
bank's capital will be expanded when the European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development invest Dollars 12.7m to acquire a 28.5 per cent stake.
State-sector company applications for 1m shares in the tranchee were not
considered. No investor has been permitted to buy more than 1 per cent of
the bank's entire equity.
Almost one-fifth of the tranchee was sold to foreign investors, who include
several banks. The sale has coincided with an unprecedented rally on the
Warsaw stock exchange, which has seen turnover in daily trading in its 16
quoted stocks more than treble since the beginning of last month to
yesterday's 203bn zlotys.
Today sees the opening of the public sale of a further 1,280,000 shares
priced at 115,000 zlotys each in the 'small' investor tranchee.
