<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Wharf bids for hotel
subsidiary's minorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHARF, the diversified Hong Kong conglomerate, is to bid HKDollars 1.22bn
(USDollars 158m) for the minorities in Harbour Centre Development, its
listed hotels subsidiary which operates the Omni chain of hotels.
Wharf already owns 56 per cent of Harbour Centre, with the Kadoorie family
owning 10.7 per cent through Hongkong and Shanghai Hotels and the remaining
33.3 per cent in the hands of the public.
Wharf will bid HKDollars 9 a share cash. This represents a 15 per cent
premium on Harbour Centre's pre-bid price of HKDollars 7.87, but a
substantial discount on the company's net asset value.
This is reckoned to be HKDollars 12.83 a share by Baring Securities and
HKDollars 11.90 a share by Wardley James Capel. A simple average of the two
valuations - HKDollars 12.36 - means Wharf's offer is at a discount of 27
per cent.
Wharf has funded the offer by placing 65m shares at HKDollars 19.50 each
with institutions. This raised HKDollars 1.27bn.
Harbour City has embarked on a recent series of acquisitions in the US and
Wharf said yesterday that it considered funding for these projects would be
substantially enhanced if Harbour City were to become wholly-owned.
</TEXT>
