FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Falling metals prices push
Asarco into loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASARCO, the integrated US copper producer, reported a first-quarter loss of
Dollars 30.9m, or 74 cents a share. A slide in metals prices and damage from
heavy rain at its biggest Arizona copper mine contributed to the loss.
The company reported a profit of Dollars 6.4m, or 16 cents, excluding
special accounting charges.
Sales were Dollars 457.1m, down from Dollars 458.9m last time.
Asarco's average realised copper price fell to 99 cents a pound in the first
three months, from Dollars 1.01 a year ago. Copper prices have continued to
slide, which would affect second-quarter results, the company said.
Lower metals prices accounted for an after-tax operating earnings decline of
Dollars 6m in the first quarter.
A scheduled 30-day maintenance shutdown of Asarco's smelter in Hayden,
Arizona, cost the company about Dollars 7m in first-quarter earnings, while
the effects of heavy rains, which continued through late February, cost the
company about Dollars 20m after tax in damage and production losses.
</TEXT>
