<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Steel recovery lifts USX for
first period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
USX Corporation, the US steel and energy group, yesterday reported net
income of Dollars 50m on sales of Dollars 4.28bn for the first three months
of 1993, compared with profits of Dollars 4m on sales of Dollars 4.11bn a
year earlier, excluding the effect of accounting changes.
Operating income rose to Dollars 163m in the latest quarter from Dollars
137m.
USX-US Steel, the Pittsburgh-based steel company, had net income of Dollars
13m, or 18 cents a share, in the 1993 quarter against an underlying net loss
of Dollars 20m, or 41 cents, a year earlier, excluding the effect of
accounting changes. Sales were flat at Dollars 1.2bn.
The group had operating income of Dollars 40m in the 1993 quarter against
restated operating income of Dollars 13m the previous year. In the latest
quarter, operating income benefited from a Dollars 28m gain from the use of
funds from a previously established insurance reserve to pay for some
employee insurance benefits.
Looking to the second quarter, the company expects operating income to
include a gain of Dollars 8m as these reserves are depleted.
In the latest quarter, the company had a pre-tax gain of Dollars 38m from
the disposal of assets.
USX-Marathon Group, the oil business, posted first-quarter net income of
Dollars 31m, or 10 cents, on sales of Dollars 3bn against underlying income
of Dollars 24m, or 8 cents on sales of Dollars 2.9bn a year ago, excluding
accounting changes in 1992.
Operating income for the group fell to Dollars 106m from a restated Dollars
124m last year.
