<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Boeing underlines aviation
downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and Reuter
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOEING, the world's biggest aircraft manufacturer, yesterday underscored the
recession in the global aerospace industry by reporting a 23 per cent drop
in first-quarter returns.
The company reported earnings of Dollars 325m, or 96 cents a share, on sales
of Dollars 6.64bn, compared with earnings of Dollars 420m, or Dollars 1.23,
on sales of Dollars 7.97bn in the same period of last year, excluding
changes in accounting practice.
The figures were broadly in line with analysts' expectations, which had
centred on earnings of around Dollars 1 a share.
The company said the drop was due mainly to lower sales of commercial
aircraft and defence and space equipment. Boeing delivered 93 commercial
aircraft during the first quarter, compared with 124 in the same period of
1992.
Commercial aircraft sales dropped from Dollars 6.54bn to Dollars 5.50bn,
while defence and space sales dipped from Dollars 1.29bn to Dollars 1.01bn.
Mr Frank Shrontz, chairman, said second-quarter sales were expected to be
somewhat higher than the first quarter, due mainly to the timing of
commercial jet deliveries, but second-half sales would be lower than the
first half, reflecting previously announced reductions in commercial
production rates.
For the full year, Boeing projected sales of some Dollars 26bn, down from
Dollars 30.2bn last year.
Boeing's annual meeting, also held yesterday, was told that the company was
studying a third version of its 777 airliner, which is currently under
development. The new version would allow a 20 per cent increase in capacity
over the two versions announced so far.
The company also confirmed it had invited aerospace groups Lockheed and
McDonnell Douglas to participate in the possible development of a new
super-jumbo jet, which it is studying with the four European partners in the
Airbus Industrie consortium. Neither company had yet replied.
Phillips Petroleum reported a first-quarter profit, compared with a loss a
year ago, higher oil and natural gas prices, Reuter reports.
Excluding special items, it had first-quarter earnings of Dollars 57m,
compared with loss of Dollars 29m a year earlier.
</TEXT>
