<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / International Company News: Falling metals prices push
Asarco to loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASARCO, the integrated US copper producer, reported a first-quarter loss of
Dollars 30.9m, or 74 cents a share. A slide in metals prices and damage from
heavy rain at its biggest Arizona copper mine contributed to the loss.
The company reported a profit of Dollars 6.4m, or 16 cents, excluding
special accounting charges. Sales were Dollars 457.1m, down from Dollars
458.9m last time.
Asarco's average realised copper price fell to 99 cents a pound in the first
three months of the year, from Dollars 1.01 a year ago.
Lead prices dropped to 20 cents, from 25 cents; zinc prices to 47 cents,
from 53 cents; and Asarco's average realised price for gold sank to Dollars
334.86 an ounce, from Dollars 373.06.
Since the quarter's end, copper prices have continued to slide, and this
would affect second-quarter results, the company said. Lower metals prices
accounted for an after-tax operating earnings decline of Dollars 6m in the
first quarter.
A scheduled 30-day maintenance shutdown of Asarco's smelter in Hayden,
Arizona, cost the company about Dollars 7m in first-quarter earnings, while
effects of heavy rains, which continued through late February, cost about
Dollars 20m after-tax in damage and production losses.
During the quarter, Asarco opened a new copper smelter in El Paso, Texas,
which is expected to reach full capacity of 110,000 tons of copper
concentrates later this year.
Phillips Petroleum reported a first-quarter profit, compared with a loss a
year ago, higher oil and natural gas prices, Reuter reports. Excluding
special items, it had first-quarter earnings of Dollars 57m, compared with
loss of Dollars 29m a year earlier.
This year's profit included a Dollars 22m workforce reduction charge, part
of continued efforts to control costs. Last year's first-quarter loss
included a Dollars 62m charge relating to job cuts.
In the latest quarter, upstream operations recorded higher earnings, while
refining, marketing and chemicals remained under pressure.
</TEXT>
