<DATE>930427
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / UK Company News: Rocking the foundations - Non-property
companies are still failing to realise the implications of the fall in
property values
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE repercussions of the collapse of the commercial property market are
spreading throughout the corporate sector.
The slump has made deep inroads into the value of property owned by British
companies, which was estimated to be worth some Pounds 224bn in 1989.
There are signs, however, that companies outside the property sector have
not yet acknowledged the scale of their problems. Some analysts argue that
the likelihood of property-related shocks is now greater for non-property
companies than for quoted property companies.
'Many non-property companies with an involvement in property have yet to
face up to reality,' says Mr Marc Gilbard of NatWest Securities. 'Almost
certainly a lot of properties are overvalued.'
Companies have been slow to acknowledge the impact of the downturn on their
balance sheets in the hope that this will prove a temporary downturn,
leading to 'no permanent diminution in value'.
This attitude may prove too complacent. Unless inflation takes off, the
recovery of property values is likely to be a long, slow haul. That alone is
a reason for companies to bite the bullet on provisions.
Another, perhaps more pressing, reason why companies should take a more
realistic view of property values stems from new accounting standards. The
Accounting Standards Board, the body that sets standards, has proposed rules
that would force companies to revalue their assets every few years.
Financial Reporting Standard 3, due to come force in June, requires
companies to base profits of property disposals on book values, rather than
historic costs. That may encourage companies to get their book values
written down as quickly as they can.
The sectors most exposed to falling property values are:
The banks, which have a three-fold exposure to property: their own branch
network, their loans to property companies and their loans to companies that
are secured against properties. Many commentators believe that the
provisions already announced fall far short of what will eventually be
needed. One recent estimate suggested that the banks could face a shortfall
of some Pounds 8bn against office property in the south-east of England.
The construction companies, many of which expanded into property development
during the 1980s. Analysts expect the UK's 10 biggest construction companies
to make provisions of up to Pounds 700m for 1992. The total provisions from
the sector may top Pounds 1bn when the write-downs from small and medium
housebuilders and construction companies are included. Already, the top 20
builders have written off a total of Pounds 800m from the book value of
housing land and developments in the four years between 1989 and 1992,
according to Warburg Securities.
The brewers, which own assets with a total value of well above Pounds 10bn
in the form of breweries, pubs, off-licences, warehouses and so on. The fall
in property prices will knock huge sums off their assets. Whitbread, for
instance, would lose some Pounds 450m from reserves if its property estate
fell by 15 per cent, as was indicated by a sample revaluation of its
property assets last November.
However, analysts believe that revaluations should not have a great impact
on share prices, since brewing stocks are increasingly bought for earnings
stream rather than asset valuation. More palpable damage could arise from
the loans made by brewers to free-trade customers that are secured on
assets.
The retail companies, for which property accounts for more than 50 per cent
of their total asset base - the largest proportion of any sector.
Traditionally, asset values have been an important component in the value of
a stores group, particularly at the time of a takeover. But the main
problems concern those companies which diversified into property development
during the 1980s. Burton, the worst-affected, was forced to write off the
value of its property developments by Pounds 169m in 1990 and Pounds 155m in
1991.
Another problem, which has escalated during the recession, relates to the
rent due on former premises, if a subsequent tenant defaults. Boots made a
provision of Pounds 5.8m in its last financial year related to 'leases where
the assignees have defaulted'.
The hotels and leisure companies, the most property-rich sector of all, with
assets of more than Pounds 30bn, according to DTZ Debenham Tewson. The link
between property prices and share prices has been weakening, however.
Property transactions of the large leisure companies accounted for 26 per
cent of pre-tax profits in 1989 according to NatWest Securities. By
contrast, their contribution was minimal for most companies last year.
A comparison of the impact of falling property values on different sectors
demonstrates that a large property exposure does not necessarily damage a
company's prospects or share price. The damage inflicted by declining asset
values depends on its involvement in property trading and development, its
gearing and the size of its reserves.
The most visible sign of falling assets appears in those companies with
development or trading properties. Those often result in large write-downs
that damage the profit and loss account. In the past they have been tucked
away as extraordinary items. Under FRS 3, that is no longer an option.
Writing down fixed assets is not necessarily a pressing problem. Falls in
values are often comfortably written off directly to the revaluation
reserve, which provides a cushion built up from past unrealised surpluses.
This process is not always as straightforward as it might seem, however. The
definition of a fixed asset proved controversial in the case of Trafalgar
House, which reclassified development properties worth Pounds 102.7m as
fixed assets in 1991, thus taking the loss through reserves rather than its
profit and loss account.
The Financial Reporting Review Panel later forced a reversal of this,
resulting in the restatement of its 1991 Pounds 122.4m profit as a loss of
Pounds 38.5m.
Another problem with write-downs of fixed assets emerges when the
revaluation reserve is wiped out, forcing further deficits to be taken
through the profit and loss account. When Ladbroke made a 15 per cent
provision against its Pounds 1bn investment property portfolio, its 1992
profits collapsed from Pounds 146.3m to Pounds 5.2m.
But perhaps the most important and widespread problem concerns companies'
ability to borrow. Companies will find it more difficult to borrow as their
gearing increases. Falling asset values may cause companies to breach their
banking covenants and will make it more difficult borrow in the future.
A recent study for the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors suggested
that a 10 per cent fall in property prices today would lead to at least a
Pounds 10bn fall in borrowing over the next two years.
The potential of falling property values to damage corporate profitability
and constrain corporate borrowing is gradually becoming increasingly
apparent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-12708</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DD1BPAFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930427
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / UK Company News: Transformation of the Triangle Trust - The
two men behind Mayflower's rapid acceleration into the fast lane
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN LESS than four years Rupert Hambro and John Simpson have transformed the
shell of Triangle Trust, the old Tri-ang toy holding company, into
Mayflower, the UK's leading automotive design and engineering group.
Barely pausing for breath in the midst of an aggressive 1-for-1 rights issue
announced a month ago to raise Pounds 34.6m, the Mayflower twosome jumped
last week to take advantage of the financial collapse of IAD (UK) to buy
Britain's leading independent automotive design house out of administrative
receivership.
Mayflower entered the automotive scene as an unknown quantity less than two
years ago with the purchase of Motor Panels out of the receivership of the
parent company CH Industrials in a deal worth Pounds 14.8m.
Now the combination of Motor Panels and International Automotive Design has
created for the first time in the UK an automotive design, engineering and
manufacturing group that has the resources to challenge some of the leading
continental European houses such as Pininfarina, Italdesign, Bertone and
Idea of Italy and Karmann of Germany.
Shaven-headed - apart from a pencil moustache - and with a taste for
colourful ties Mr Simpson, chief executive of Mayflower, has begun to cut a
distinctive figure behind the scenes of the motor industry.
With the backing of Rupert Hambro as non-executive chairman, he is well on
his way to achieving his ambition of building a Pounds 100m public company.
Mayflower currently has a market capitalisation of about Pounds 95.5m. Its
turnover of Pounds 67.8m last year, which was forecast to rise to some
Pounds 70m this year, will now advance by about Pounds 40m in a full year
through the addition of IAD.
The company has grown rapidly out of the opportunities and problems facing
Mr Simpson and Mr Hambro by the late 1980s.
Mr Hambro, who broke away from Hambros Bank with his father and two brothers
in 1986 to establish JO Hambro in corporate finance and investment
management, had a problem of what to do with Triangle Trust, a loss-making,
publicly-quoted company.
Hambro had bought into the company as an investment opportunity but had
failed to make a go of the group's operations spread across toymaking,
financial services and advertising.
Mr Simpson, aged 50, was looking for a vehicle to gain a stock market
quotation for his privately-owned mini-conglomerate Timelaw (RPHM), which by
1989 chiefly comprised Ribbons, a maker of webbing for seatbelts, parachutes
and other safety harnesses, and a direct marketing company PHM.
Prior to setting up in business on his own account, Mr Simpson's main
commercial experience had been with Bunzl, where at the age of 28 he had
been one of the company's youngest divisional managing directors responsible
for the Rolex Paper Company.
The two decided to join forces. In 1989 Triangle Trust paid Mr Simpson and
his business partners Pounds 11.2m for Timelaw - Pounds 4.5m in cash and the
rest in shares. Mr Simpson became chief executive with Rupert Hambro staying
as non-executive chairman. The company's name was changed to Mayflower.
Of their respective roles Mr Hambro says: 'I bring the City connections. I
act as a sounding board. John Simpson and David Donnelly, the finance
director, run the industrial operations and acquisitions.'
Mr Simpson was set on expanding his new company in engineering and
manufacturing. Motor Panels was the first big opportunity to arise.
Such opportunities do not come easily. By the time IAD fell into
administrative receivership three weeks ago, it was the 111th company that
Mayflower had looked at. It had previously had contacts with International
Automotive Design and Mr John Shute, its pugnacious founder and chairman,
but the price had always been too high. IAD's receivership changed the two
groups fortunes.
In 1989 the Cinvest venture capital group had bought into IAD, acquiring a
13.5 per cent interest for Pounds 4.5m which valued the group at Pounds 33m.
Mayflower has now paid Pounds 3.25m in cash to acquire the IAD business and
assets from the receiver together with the shares of IAD's overseas trading
subsidiaries, which did not go into receivership.
The combination of IAD's established design expertise and international
reputation in the world auto industry and Motor Panels' greater experience
in manufacturing could now produce a highly effective combination in the
intensely competitive world arena for automotive design, engineering and
manufacturing services.
Motor Panels, the Coventry-based automotive engineering group, already
operates in vehicle engineering design and development through to tooling
and manufacturing.
Before the IAD acquisition Mayflower was already expanding rapidly and was
in the midst of its second rights issue in less than two years with the
Pounds 34.6m it was already raising aimed at financing its existing
ambitious expansion in the UK and the US.
It raised about Pounds 17m in 1991 to buy Motor Panels.
Mayflower increased its pre-tax profit to Pounds 1.7m last year on turnover
of Pounds 67.8m and with a workforce worldwide of close to 1,000.
IAD incurred a loss of Pounds 105,000 on turnover of Pounds 62m for the year
to the end of April 1991, its last audited accounts. It also has a workforce
approaching 1,000 worldwide, including a large number of independent
consultants, with just under 300 in the UK. It suffered 'substantial losses'
of Pounds 2m to Pounds 2.5m in the last 12 months.
Based at Worthing, West Sussex, IAD has carried out contracts for many of
the world's leading vehicle makers since it was formed by Mr Shute in 1976.
It has established a presence in most of the world's leading car producing
countries with subsidiaries in Germany, France, Spain and the US and liaison
offices in Tokyo, Seoul and Moscow.
IAD has played a leading role in the design and prototype development of a
wide range of vehicles including the Ford Scorpio estate car, Ford's Lincoln
Town Car in the US, the Volvo 440, the Mazda MX-5 sports car and the
three-door Fiat Tipo as well as electric and light commercial vehicles.
The Motor Panels business in the UK and in the US has recently won, or is at
an advanced stage of negotiations on, several large contracts.
Even before the IAD takeover Mayflower had moved into the fast lane and
expected capital investment to jump from Pounds 3m in 1992 to about Pounds
23m this year, chiefly for the development of its plants and equipment in
the UK and in the US.
Its turnover more than doubled last year to Pounds 67.8m (Pounds 27.4m), and
Mr Simpson had forecast that turnover would rise to Pounds 110m-Pounds 120m
by 1995, before IAD dropped into Mayflower's lap.
Privately owned, IAD was brought down by a lack of financial resources in
recession.
Mayflower is seeking not to repeat the mistake. At the time of the rights
issue it had a Pounds 1.4m cash balance and no bank borrowings. Gearing was
expected to rise to only 26 per cent in 1994, when the Motor Panels
expansion programme was expected to be at its peak. IAD will worsen the
ratios, but according to Mr Simpson the opportunity was too good to be
missed.
</TEXT>
