<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Willis likely to be succeeded by deputy as head of TUC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Willis, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, yesterday
announced he would take early retirement after the TUC's annual congress in
September.
Mr Willis, aged 60, has held his post for nine years. Although tributes to
his past work came from both inside and outside the union movement
yesterday, there has been criticism over the years of his leadership style
and, in particular, his lack of impact as a public speaker.
The next TUC general secretary is likely to be Mr John Monks, aged 47, the
current deputy general secretary. Nominations from affiliated unions for the
post will be open until mid-July and an election at this year's congress in
Brighton will follow if more than one candidate stands.
Mr Willis said he had considered retiring last year but had postponed the
decision because of the TUC's campaign to save miners' jobs.
One factor which may have persuaded him to announce his retirement at this
point was the recent vote by members of the Amalgamated Engineering and
Electrical Union to affiliate to the TUC. The vote came five years after
members of the EETPU electricians' union, now a section of the AEEU, was
expelled from the TUC for breaking its rules over poaching members from
other unions.
Mr Willis said he had been 'greatly encouraged' by the vote which had paved
the way for the organised unity the TUC needed. 'However, given that other
serious problems and challenges may persist, I believe that the new thrust
of trade union drive and leadership can best be sustained by electing a new
general secretary now to carry out those responsibilities for some years
ahead,' he said.
Mr Alan Tuffin, TUC president, said Mr Willis had 'led the TUC through a
period when the trade union movement has come under unprecedented and
sustained attack'. Under his leadership the TUC had 'still found positive
ways of moving forward', Mr Tuffin added.
Mr Neil Kinnock, former Labour leader, said: 'In destructive times Norman
Willis has never stopped being constructive. Norman's sense of justice and
his sense of humour have both been irrepressible.'
Mr Geoff Armstrong, director general of the Institute of Personnel
Management, said Mr Willis's unfailing good humour probably did much to hold
the movement together and avoid disaster.
Trade union membership has fallen by more than 25 per cent to 7.7m since Mr
Willis first took office, creating severe financial problems for the TUC -
both staffing levels at headquarters and activities have been reduced.
Tasks facing new boss, Page 18
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
