<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An animal with eyes on stalks and lots of legs will terrify people even if
humans are thousands of times bigger and heavier, but such is our
anthropomorphism that a much bigger animal will cause cooings of delight if
it simply does something supposedly characteristic of humans. Hence the
appeal of the meerkat, which looks like a cross between a dog and a monkey
and stands on its hind legs to watch for predators. 'Meerkats United' is
repeated today in David Attenborough's Wildlife 100 collection (7.00 BBC1).
In today's The Great Picture Trail National Gallery director Neil MacGregor
talks about Velasquez's 'Old Woman Cooking Eggs' and Manet's 'Bar At The
Folies Bergere' which, for some reason, always seems to be chosen, as here,
for any collection of reproductions destined for the walls of schools (7.35
BBC2). BBC2's foreign affairs series Assignment screens the programme about
the illegal export of religious icons from Russia which was postponed last
week (7.45). 40 Minutes considers the life of comedian Ernie Wise without
his teammate, the late Eric Morecambe (9.50 BBC2).
</TEXT>
