<PROFILE>_AN-DD1BPADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930427
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Buoyant Tories put money on
economic upturn - The issues dominating the likely two-horse race for next
month's Newbury by-election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR PEOPLE who could trample on the green shoots of Mr John Major's
political spring, the voters of Newbury appear remarkably calm about their
opportunity.
The risks for the prime minister are considerable. Defeat in the by-election
next Thursday would cut the government's overall majority at Westminster to
19. It would also threaten the fragile confidence beginning to emerge among
Tory MPs, especially if it was coupled with a poor performance in the county
council elections on the same day.
Liberal Democrat by-election victories in the last parliament showed that
the 9.3 per cent swing which the party would need to take the seat  - held
by the Tories with a majority of 12,300 last April - should be well within
their grasp. But they still need to find the issue to set their campaign
alight.
In villages such as Lambourn on the Berkshire downs, it is easy to see how
the constituency has been solidly Tory since 1924. In the more suburban
parts of the constituency such as Thatcham and in Newbury itself, a market
town of just under 40,000, the presence of a consistent Liberal challenge is
more apparent.
The Tory candidate is Mr Julian Davidson, the determinedly buoyant
30-year-old who fought Mr Paddy Ashdown in Yeovil in the general election.
Although his own family firm has been a victim of the recession, Mr
Davidson's message is relentlessly positive about the prospects for the
economy, and for Newbury, and particularly for the two together if he wins
the seat. It is a re-run of the general election campaign: 'vote Tory on
Thursday for recovery on Friday'.
Mr David Rendel, his Liberal Democrat opponent, has a better doorstep
manner, his attentive concern honed by four general elections as well as
involvement in local politics.
For Labour, it scarcely matters that Mr Steve Billcliffe is a competent and
irreproachably local candidate - the party polled fewer than 4,000 votes
last April. It is even split about whether it would prefer a Tory or a
Liberal Democrat victory.
Although the contest is a two-horse race, it has attracted a record 19
candidates. Beyond the usual fringe contenders are three candidates in
favour of a referendum on Maastricht, a Give the Royal Billions to Schools
candidate, and a Defence of Children's Humanity in Bosnia candidate.
On the doorstep, however, the main issue is the economy.
The constituency is still prosperous though not at the level of its
expectations in the 1980s boom years, when high-tech companies took
advantage of its prime location on the M4 corridor.
House prices have collapsed, and the unemployment rate of just under 7.5 per
cent is much higher than it was a few years ago, though it is still below
the national average.
Even so, the will to punish the government for the recession has been
weakened by some encouraging economic signs locally as well as nationally.
There are also more specialised concerns. The racing industry, an important
local employer, emphasises that the Budget decision on value added tax on
bloodstock has been a critical element in retaining support for the
Conservatives.
Mr Rendel's anti-hunting stance is suspect in such a rural area, but among
farmers the government's handling of the integrated administration and
control system is even more unpopular.
The only specific national issue to show signs of dominating has been the
Tories' unpopular Budget decision to impose VAT on domestic fuel.
While Mr Rendel says the tax change has aroused 'very strong anger', the
mood is not yet like the fury over the poll tax, which swept away a Tory
majority of 19,000 in the Ribble Valley by-election. He has also seemed
surprisingly ill-prepared for the Tory counter-attack over the Liberal
Democrat commitment to a carbon tax.
To win, the Liberal Democrats need to make VAT on domestic fuel more of a
focus for widespread anger about Conservative broken promises, and make
people believe that a vote for them will mean change. Otherwise, the Tories
look set to win by a short head.
</TEXT>
