FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lilley pressed over benefits policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS aimed at focusing social security benefits increasingly on those
in need were among the options being considered by the government, Mr Peter
Lilley, social security secretary, told MPs yesterday.
He also confirmed that during the lifetime of the present parliament the
government was committed to maintaining the basic retirement pension and
uprating child benefit in line with inflation.
Mr Donald Dewar, the shadow social security secretary, pressed in vain for
more information about the policy papers discussed at the week-end by
ministers engaged in the long-term review of social security policy.
Mr Lilley declined to comment on whether a decision in principle had been
taken that those on middle incomes and above should be asked to opt out of
the basic state retirement pension, and, ultimately, from sickness and
unemployment benefit as well.
Miss Ann Widdecombe, junior social secretary, attacked Mr David Winnick,
Labour MP for Walsall North, for saying that the basic retirement pension
was no longer safe in the government's hands.
The Treasury estimates that only about 1 per cent of the additional yield
from extending VAT to all fuel and power is likely to be paid by charities,
Sir John Cope, the paymaster general, said yesterday.
'We expect almost all of the remaining additional yield will be in respect
of private households, though there is no reliable information on the
expenditure by non-private households on fuel and power.'
