<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tory backbenchers urge rethink on
oil tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR TORY backbenchers last night called on the government to revise its
proposed changes to the North Sea tax regime following an outcry in the oil
industry. Many companies say the government's changes to petroleum revenue
taxes would lead to a halving of exploration activity and the loss of up to
40,000 jobs.
Mr John Butterfill, Conservative MP for Bournemouth East, tabled an
amendment to the Finance Bill which would provide some transitional relief
for oil companies affected by the tax changes.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, proposed in the Budget a reduction in the
PRT rate from 75 per cent to 50 per cent and the abolition of tax relief for
exploratory drilling.
Mr John Watts, Tory chairman of the Treasury and Civil Service committee,
also urged a change to the transitional relief proposals.
In moving the oil taxation 'pendulum' from one extreme to another, the
government may have gone too far, Mr Watts said.
Speaking as the finance bill im-plementing the Budget measures received its
second Commons reading, Mr Watts said transitional relief should be allowed
in cases where companies had contractual obligations to incur expenditure
that had been entered into in the expectation that relief would apply.
Mr Butterfill, vice-chairman of the Tory Backbench finance committee, has
suggested that tax relief for exploration work to which the industry is
already commited is maintained. This could be paid for by raising the PRT
rate to 55 per cent until the end of December 1996.
The proposal addresses one of the industry's prime concerns about the new
tax regime. Many explorers were angry that tax relief would not apply to
wells they had committed to drill as part of their applications to the
Department of Trade and Industry for oil exploration licences.
The industry has committed to drill between 160 and 180 wells which would
have qualified for tax relief under the previous regime. Although the
Treasury says those wells are not legally binding, Mr Tim Eggar, industry
minister, confirmed - in a parliamentary answer - that he expects the
industry to stick to obligations made under previous licensing rounds.
Winding up last night's finance bill debate, Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial
secretary to the Treasury, adopted a conciliatory tone, saying the
government recognised the need to avoid 'unnecessary dislocation' and would
endeavour to do so.
Labour and the Scottish National party both joined the calls for a rethink.
For Labour, Ms Harriet Harman, a frontbench Treasury spokeswoman, said it
was 'extraordinary' that the Finance Bill contained oil taxation measures
which 'on the chancellor's own admission' would result in at least 10,000
job losses.
</TEXT>
