<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Cross-party calls for curb on
budget deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY MPs yesterday joined Labour in urging further action to control the
government's budget deficit, as a Commons committee published a report
highly critical of last month's Budget.
The most critical part of the report by the Treasury and Civil Service
committee followed an ambush by opposition MPs which led to the inclusion of
a call for chancellor Norman Lamont to be replaced by someone 'who can
inspire more trust'.
This was not backed by Tory committee members, who also voted against the
report as a whole being adopted. But Conservative MPs made clear yesterday
that they shared the committee's misgivings on a variety of other issues.
Principal among these was the committee's concern that the measures
announced in the March Budget would not be enough to meet the government's
objective of bringing its budget towards balance over the economic cycle.
If the government was to achieve such a balance, further action in the form
of tax increases or cuts in public spending would be required, the report
said.
The report also expressed concern that a current account deficit of as much
as 2 per cent of gross domestic product should exist 'at the trough of a
very long and deep recession'.
It drew a comparison with the 2.6 per cent surplus at the trough of the 1981
recession and concurred with the Bank of England that this deficit
represented a 'fundamental weakness in the economy'.
On mortgages and housing finance, the committee accused the government of
embarking 'by stealth' on a policy of phasing out mortgage tax relief by
limiting its range of coverage and the rate of relief. Mr Lamont should 'now
make this policy explicit and explain the reasons behind it,' it said.
While Labour hailed the report as 'a landmark', Mr John Watts, the
committee's Tory chairman, admitted the manoeuvrings might affect the
seriousness with which the government took its 'more reasoned criticism'.
The March 1993 Budget. HMSO. Pounds 21.70.
</TEXT>
