<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Portillo signals pay crackdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Portillo yesterday warned that the government would not break its
public expenditure targets, as he underlined the root and branch nature of
its departmental spending review.
As the finance bill implementing the measures in last month's Budget
received its second Commons reading, the chief secretary to the Treasury
also signalled a renewed crackdown on wages.
Sustaining Britain's competitive advantage would depend on controlling costs
'wage costs in particular', he said. Wage restraint would 'help business to
compete' and assist in the creation of new jobs.
In a combative speech, Mr Portillo sought to portray the government's battle
to control public spending as for the good of the whole economy. If public
spending was too high, it weighed upon the 'wealth-creating sector of our
country', he said.
Offering a coded warning to cabinet ministers as the new round of
public-spending discussions starts he predicted that the government's
spending would grow at a slower rate than overall growth in the economy over
time. He said the government had published fixed spending ceilings 'above
which we will not go.'
Seeking to buttress his argument with statistics, Mr Portillo said central
government debt interest payments were projected to rise by nearly 9 per
cent a year in real terms between now and 1996-97.
This alone would add close to 1 per cent to the proportion of national
income taken by public spending, which is planned to weigh in at over 45 per
cent in the current financial year.
Turning to his rolling four-year public spending review, Mr Portillo said he
had agreed 'demanding agendas' with the four cabinet ministers whose
big-spending departments had been initially targeted.
'We have chosen these programmes because they are among the largest - what
is loose change in these programmes can be more than the entire budget for
another department,' he said.
Ms Harriet Harman, a front-bench Labour Treasury spokesman, took the
government to task for breaking its pre-election pledges not to raise taxes,
while Mr Alan Beith, the Liberal Democrats' Treasury spokesman, urged
ministers to remember that they meant 'we are climbing out of the hole into
which the government pushed us'.
The bill received a second reading by 310 votes to 266, a government
majority of 44.
</TEXT>
