FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pressure over Jubilee line deal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS have come under pressure from both Labour and Liberal Democrat MPs
over the question of government guarantee or underwriting as a result of the
deal by which the European Investment Bank agreed to provide Pounds 98m
towards the extension of the Jubilee line.
The EIB is a public sector institution owned by the European Community
member states, which usually lends to public sector projects underwritten by
governments.
Mr Steven Norris, the junior transport minister, said yesterday that the
detailed arrangements were still being discussed and were subject to
commercial confidentiality.
There were signs, however, that once the negotiations had been concluded
ministers would be more forthcoming about the arrangements between London
Transport, London Underground and the parties involved in financing Canary
Wharf which should allow the Jubilee line extension to go ahead.
