FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Challenge renewed on social chapter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to ensure that MPs can have an effective vote on the social chapter
have already been renewed in advance of the next stage of the marathon
debate on the Maastricht treaty.
Both the Labour frontbench team and Mr Bill Cash, a leading Tory
Euro-sceptic, have re-tabled the amendment excluding the social protocol
from the bill ratifying the treaty.
While Labour MPs are concentrating on the social chapter, almost 60
amendments have been tabled so far by various Euro-sceptics on both sides of
the Commons.
Their determination not to relax their efforts has been fuelled by anger
over the comments of Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, who signalled
at the weekend that the UK intended to join other EC countries in closer
economic and political co-operation even if Denmark rejected Maastricht in
its referendum next month.
Last night, former Tory party chairman and prominent Euro-sceptic Lord
Tebbit said: 'If his (Mr Hurd's) words have any meaning they can mean only
that the pledge he gave at Edinburgh - the pledges of the prime minister,
too - were not matters of honour, just words to help get the Maastricht bill
through parliament.'
