FT  27 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Teachers' plea on testing rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SIX unions representing school teachers in England and Wales yesterday
united to urge Mr John Patten, the education secretary, to suspend the
controversial national curriculum tests for 1993, John Willman writes.
The unions called in a letter for the suspension of the tests pending the
review of the national curriculum and testing by Sir Ron Dearing,
newly-appointed chairman of the two government advisory bodies on school
education.
Mr Patten immediately dismissed the appeal as 'an extraordinary suggestion'.
He said it would lead to the scrapping of the tests for seven-year-olds, now
in their third year, in spite of 'overwhelming evidence that they are
helping push up standards'.
The appeal brought together the Professional Association of Teachers and the
two headteachers' unions with the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers which is boycotting the tests. These
were joined by the National Union of Teachers and the Association of
Teachers and Lecturers, both of which are balloting members over a boycott.
The appeal came as the government launched a Pounds 700,000 publicity
campaign to win support for the national curriculum tests for schools in
England and Wales.
