<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Hard evidence of recovery eludes northern professionals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A PRIVATE dining room at Worsley Old Hall, Greater Manchester, an
informal luncheon club of a dozen members of various professions was
searching for tangible reasons to believe recovery is under way. Among these
people, who included lawyers, actuaries, accountants and consultants, faith
was in short supply.
A generally agreed perspective was provided by Mr Len Collinson, chairman of
Collinson Grant, a local management consultancy. He said: 'We have a number
of clients who are doing better, but it's against very bad results last year
and the year before. Things can only get better because they could hardly
have got worse, short of people going out of business.'
Times are tougher than they look in professional services, which experienced
remarkable growth in Manchester and Leeds during the latter half of the
1980s.
Professionals have been putting up a good front but Mr Graeme Jump, partner
in charge of the Manchester office of Mace &amp; Jones, said what many of his
fellow solicitors have kept quiet about.
'Three or four years ago, corporate lawyers used to boast about how much
they could charge for their time,' he said. 'They pushed prices up and
clients hardly ever protested. Not now. Prices are negotiable downwards.
Real fee levels are probably down 30 to 40 per cent on two years ago.'
Mr Jump added that job prospects are poor in corporate legal services: 'For
the first time since the 1960s there are trainees coming to the end of their
articles who are unable to find jobs.'
Mr Dennis Wright, a director of Reeves Brown Associates, a firm of
actuaries, echoed this: 'The very idea of an unemployed actuary used to be
unthinkable. Now there are very many.'
Nor are professional groups particularly buoyant on Humberside, where the
Humber's four large ports and myriad smaller wharves have been growing with
export trade to Europe during the recession.
Mr Roger King, a partner in Kidsons Impey accountants of Hull, told the
luncheon club last week: 'My clients say any recovery is extremely slow. In
the construction industry, it's non-existent. The accountancy profession is
suffering redundancies all over the country. There are many newly qualified
accountants who have completed their training but cannot be kept on.'
There are some hopeful signs, however. North West Business Insider, the
regional business magazine, has surveyed Manchester advertising agencies and
found this year's budgets were 25 per cent up on last year. Corporate
finance activity was also up as medium-sized companies turned to
professionals in this field for advice on how to prepare themselves for
economic recovery.
</TEXT>
