<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / The City Bombing: Damage insurer assesses itself
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOTTLES OF Evian water, briefcases, jackets and nine worried executives were
cluttering up the office of Mr Guy Belcher, managing director of Richard
Sparrow, a London firm of reinsurance brokers yesterday.
Mr Belcher himself was sitting outside with his secretaries and other
colleagues as the directors of Macey Williams, a Lloyd's insurance broker
that had been bombed out, scoured the City for somewhere to do their
business for the next six months.
Among other parts of the business, Macey Williams provides insurance cover
for bomb damage to property companies. This time it found itself on the
receiving end. It is based in St Helen's Place close to the heart of
Saturday's City bomb blast.
Mr Roger Macey, the managing director, began drawing up emergency plans on
Saturday evening but it wasn't until yesterday that someone managed to
inspect the damage.
He said the company had been offered one office at Pounds 75 per sq ft which
he said was 'far too high'. Other rentals were close to Pounds 20 per sq ft
not far from the Pounds 18 which the company had been paying.
Directors came in and out throughout the afternoon to report on
possibilities. One site seemed ideal at 3,000 sq ft but had no telephone
points. 'We'll keep trying until we find somewhere, but we will,' said Mr
Macey. Mr Belcher said: 'If they don't get anywhere then they'll have my
office again tomorrow. That's how the Lloyd's community helps each other.'
Other executives were visiting the bombed premises, getting past police
barriers by wearing white hard hats and using side entrances. The company,
Mr Macey said, needed to get its files, fax machines and other equipment out
but he did not know at that stage whether a removal lorry would be granted
access.
He said the company had been unable to write much business but had still
managed to take two orders. 'We shall need our Macey Williams paper slips to
go to Lloyd's so that will mean another sortie tomorrow,' he said.
</TEXT>
