<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / The City Bombing: Japanese banks undeterred by damage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE banks in London yesterday said they would not be deterred from
doing business in the City as a result of the weekend bomb, despite severe
damage to the offices of two leading Japanese institutions.
Tokai Bank, the largest in Japan, had four floors in the Hongkong and
Shanghai Bank tower, one of the buildings most severely damaged in the
blast.
'London is an international finance centre and doing business there is
necessary,' Tokai said. 'The bomb doesn't damage that image, but the risk is
increasing. We will have to consider how to reduce the risks for our
operations.'
The Long Term Credit Bank of Japan, one of a small group of long-term
financing institutions, was also forced out by the bomb, and has moved into
temporary accommodation with two other Japanese banks, Mitsubishi and Daichi
Europe.
Other Japanese institutions hit by the two City bombs over the last year
include Mitsubishi Corporation Finance, the financing arm of the Mitsubishi
trading group, whose office was devastated over the weekend, and Sanwa Bank,
which was forced out of offices in the Commercial Union building last year.
The general reaction from Japanese financial institutions was that they must
maintain a presence in London regardless of the risk. But the blast comes as
many of these institutions, still troubled by bad loans at home, are
reviewing or trimming international operations.
Japanese securities houses have cut expatriate staff in London as part of
general shifting of resources out of Europe to take advantage of higher
growth in Asia. A brokerage official said terrorism in London was one more
reason to send fewer Japanese expatriate staff, but would not of itself
prompt the company to bring staff home.
'Japanese know that the IRA has exploded bombs in the past, but the attacks
on the City give us a different feeling. We wonder why they are attacking
financial targets, and it does make us feel a bit uneasy,' the broker said.
The Bank of Tokyo ordered a security assessment before a recent move to new
London premises, which were unaffected by the explosion. The latest incident
appears to have confirmed the wisdom of the assessment.
Mitsubishi Bank will review the security of its offices in London, which
were not damaged. Sumitomo Bank, another leading Japanese institution, said:
'We are gathering information and will consider what action should be
taken.'
</TEXT>
