<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / The City Bombing: Loss assessors see little that can be
salvaged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WATER poured through the ceiling of a wrecked sandwich shop, 50 yards from
the crater caused by Saturday's bomb blast. Mr Justin Balcombe, of loss
assessors Balcombe Group, wanders over, treading carefully through twisted
metal window fittings, rubble and fragments of glass littering Bishopsgate.
'It's not the water main. It's a sprinkler that's gone off,' he says, noting
the details carefully. This could be useful information for a claim.
With his colleague Mr John Gale, the group's deputy managing director, Mr
Balcombe has been examining damage since early yesterday, sometimes
following up inquiries from anxious shop owners and businessmen, who are
still denied access to the area, sometimes - as in this case - simply
collecting information.
Saturday's attack has brought a flood of inquiries to Balcombe Group, which
advises companies on insurance coverage and claims. Both men are convinced
that the loss will be greater than that caused by the Baltic Exchange bomb
last year, and insist that total claims will exceed Pounds 1bn.
They believe structural damage to be far heavier than in last year's bomb.
'If this building is not pulled down it will be a miracle,' says Mr Gale,
pointing to an office building beside the remnants of St Ethelburga's
church.
Balcombe's preliminary assessments of half a dozen properties have shown
that very little is salvageable. Claims for lighting and other office
furniture and fittings will also mount up into hefty sums. In the buildings
closest to the blast daggers of glass still hang uneasily from the windows.
Removing glass and securing buildings will take at least a further week.
The firm expects claims for interruption to business - what insurers call
B/I - to swell the size of the total loss. B/I accounted for about a third
of the Pounds 300m of damage caused by last April's bombs.
Demolition work will inevitably mean curbs on access to the area even after
workers return, reducing customers and hindering suppliers. 'Restriction of
access will be covered under some insurance policies,' says Mr Balcombe.
Damage to telecommunications links and gas, electricity and water supplies
will slow construction work. 'It is going to take months to reroute them,'
he adds.
At the wrecked Bishopsgate branch of Pret a Manger, the takeaway food chain,
Mr Sinclair Beecham, the chain's owner, has asked Balcombe to help with an
overall claim for several hundred thousand pounds, of which B/I will amount
to over half.
Wearing an unfamiliar hard hat, he surveys staff cleaning up broken glass
and predicts it could be months before the shop will open again. 'There are
no customers out there. There will be no one out there for a while.'
</TEXT>
