<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / The City Bombing: Search for greater security gets under way
/ A look at the questions the City must answer if it is to strengthen its
protection against further terrorist attacks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHOULD there be more police on the streets to enforce parking restrictions
and check on suspicious vehicles?
Following the bomb attack last year in St Mary Axe, the Corporation of
London increased the number of police officers by 40 at a cost of Pounds
1.5m. The extra cost was borne mainly by the big financial institutions
which bear the burden of the corporation's Pounds 700m annual budget.
The corporation likes to claim that a bomb discovered in Stoke Newington,
north of the City, before last year's Lord Mayor's Show, did not end up
being left in the City as a result of the heavy police presence. But this
alone cannot stop bomb attacks - and didn't last weekend. In Northern
Ireland, a large police presence and additional troops have not prevented
bomb attacks. Should there be more regular checks on vehicles which are
circulating in London?
The police would like to carry out more checks at irregular intervals in
order to wrongfoot potential terrorists. They are seeking more powers to do
so but feel that their powers of detention on suspicion are restrained under
the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984. There is a specific restriction
against the police setting up permanent road blocks to check vehicles. The
police themselves worry about the potential of turning areas of the mainland
into new versions of Ulster, which would be considered a victory by the IRA.
Are there other ways of regulating traffic flow in the City?
Three streets in the City have been turned into pedestrian precincts, and
plans to pedestrianise other areas are likely to be hastened. Some back
streets have already been closed off since last year's bomb - Throgmorton
Street, for instance, which runs behind the Stock Exchange and the Bank of
England. This, and moves to discourage the use of private cars, could lead
to a concentration of commercial vehicles on to main thoroughfares, reducing
the areas that need to be policed.
Are the City's buildings adequately protected against bomb blasts?
Short of rebuilding offices with reinforced concrete of the kind that might
be used in a nuclear fall-out shelter, no material is available that can
protect a building which is next to a bomb blast.
Some City buildings gain some protection through the use of laminated glass
with special frames, plastic film on windows or protective curtains, or
mobile laminated fibreglass mat screens. These can minimise the risk of
injury by flying glass by about 95 per cent and reduce the potential damage
to equipment.
The costs involved could be reduced if additional security were built in at
an early construction phase rather than as a replacement.
To fit out a 30ft by 20ft reception area in a City office with laminated
glass can cost about Pounds 750,000.
Is there adequate co-ordination of security strategies between the police
and businesses operating in the City?
Some security advisers think not. The problem is that companies tend to
devise their own security policies without co-ordinating with each other and
do not have serious forward planning on the issue. The corporation says that
some businesses did get together with their neighbours to co-ordinate their
security after last year's bomb, although it has not attempted to
co-ordinate or encourage such action. Could private businesses be doing more
to guard against terrorist acts?
Police say yes - increased vigilance by company security staff, and better
co-ordination with police. At least one large commercial establishment has
been working closely with its private security advisers to monitor vehicles.
Would increased use of video cameras help?
Videos, together with additional technology capable of enhancing wide-angle
images, can be used to provide evidence on the culprits of a bomb but do not
necessarily guarantee prevention. There are about two dozen cameras in use
to monitor traffic on the City's main streets, although few of these are
linked to video recorders. The corporation said it would consider extending
the use of cameras.
Is the City more vulnerable than other financial centres?
It is, not so much because it is less protected, but because the IRA is
better organised and better resourced than any other terrorist organisation.
Terrorist attacks on the European mainland are not on the scale they were in
the 1970s and rarely involve destruction of property.
Nonetheless in Frankfurt the Bundesbank has barriers supervised by armed
police while businesspeople and bankers are known to be protected by
personal bodyguards. Some senior executives use private lifts and work in
offices without windows. In New York co-ordination of anti-terrorist
policing under the FBI did not prevent the recent bomb at the World Trade
Center. One of the main criticisms launched at anti-terrorism measures in
the UK is that the security forces are too fragmented.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
