<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / The City Bombing: Safety net catches displaced dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WE HADN'T planned to test things out so soon,' says Mr Philip Lovell,
general manager of Safetynet Trading Places, an emergency computer back-up
facility on the fringes of the City.
Workmen are carrying in fax machines and paper. A photocopier has been
delivered. Engineers are installing telephones.
Trading Places - which has the capacity for three small City dealing rooms
and back-up operations - opened last Wednesday after three months of fitting
out.
Eight dealers and a dozen support staff from Tokai Bank were working in the
centre from first thing yesterday. Another room was being kitted out for use
by an unnamed bank.
Mr Lovell says the blast has provided 40 per cent of the company's annual
budgeted revenues. 'From a business point of view it has been good, though
we hadn't planned it to come as a result of this awful event,' he says. Most
use of the rooms results from more mundane events  - such as floods and
engineering failures.
Mr Hamid Noorizadeh, assistant general manager at Tokai Bank - based at the
now devastated Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Bank building at 99 Bishopsgate - said he
heard of the bombing on Saturday morning, but that contingency plans had
been laid last year.
'We haven't lost anything,' he says. 'We were able to retrieve all our
accounting and treasury data from back-up computer information stored
off-site. But we cannot trade as actively as we would have.'
