<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Travel industry attacks government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is likely to face legal action over its failure to provide
package holiday travellers with the protection required by a European
Community directive, Mr Mike Grindrod, president of the Association of
British Travel Agents, said yesterday.
He told an association convention in Majorca that package tour regulations
which came into force at the beginning of the year were an 'un-satisfactory
mishmash'.
The directive requires all companies to have bonding or insurance
arrangements to ensure customers can be re-patriated or receive their money
back in the event of corporate collapse. Mr Grindrod criticised the
government for allowing companies to make their own arrangements outside
recognised trade organisations.
If a failed travel operator had insufficient insurance, travellers would
merely have the consolation of knowing that the company faced a fine. They
would have no means of getting their money back.
Mr Grindrod said: 'Lewis Carroll at his most imaginative could never have
invented anything as topsy-turvy and through a cracked looking glass as Her
Majesty's government has concocted.
'Eventually I am convinced that a future British government, either
voluntarily as a matter of policy or having been hauled kicking and
screaming before the European court, will amend the regulations to provide a
statutory guarantee.'
</TEXT>
