<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / 'For sale' boards go up at mines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR SALE OR LEASE: 20 coal mines, many loss-making and none wanted by their
owner. Required to compete in a fast-shrinking market of uncertain size.
Not perhaps the most tempting of public-sector assets to be offered to the
private sector, but enough to have already attracted the attention of 22
companies which have expressed an interest to British Coal.
In a month or so British Coal is likely to start advertising the first of
the pits it is closing or mothballing for sale or lease.
It will be another three or four months at least before the first of the
companies takes control of a pit.
The timetable must seem grindingly slow to companies such as RJB Mining and
Edwards Energy, which are among the frontrunners.
The apparent tardiness of the process has already been criticised by MPs.
However, Mr Neil Clarke, the British Coal chairman, says that the
corporation is moving as fast as possible.
'The principle is established: it is reasonable that if we have decided to
close a colliery, we should make it available to someone else,' he said
yesterday.
He described the process as 'enormously complicated'. The corporation must
take account of consultations with unions, competition law, the 1947
Nationalisation Act and the Transfer of Undertakings regulations of the
European Community.
There has been opposition by unions to the proposal by British Coal to
consult on the closure of all 10 pits collectively. This particular issue is
likely to be settled in the High Court.
Only when the closure procedure for each pit is over will British Coal start
the hiving-off process. Newspaper advertisements will invite expressions of
interest, which will entitle a bidder to detailed information on a colliery
and a chance to visit it.
Shortly after that it will become clear which bidders are serious.
Mr Ray Proctor, the British Coal executive heading the operation, said the
corporation intended to operate a competitive open-tender system, with a
'pre-qualifying process'.
He said: 'It will not be like sending off your application for a driving
licence and getting it back within a few days. Success will not just depend
on the level of someone's bid. We will be checking out the financial and
technical competence of bidders.'
British Coal is unlikely to look favourably upon companies intent on 'rape
and pillage' operations - mining easily accessible coal but doing no
development work.
'We do not want short-term bursts of output that will displace the coal of
collieries with long-term prospects,' said Mr Proctor.
The corporation will use consultants to help assess bidders and, said Mr
Clark, to ensure that licensing is 'judicial rather than arbitrary'.
Bidders will have to think long and hard before buying - the pits are being
discarded by British Coal because there is apparently nowhere to sell their
output. Nor will the size of the potential market become apparent until
British Coal concludes contracts for additional tonnages with the
electricity generators. That might not be achieved before October.
Most independent operators expect to concentrate on niche markets.
'We are running a system that is geared to the electricity supply industry
but gives some output for the domestic and industrial markets,' says Mr
Proctor. 'They (the independents) are seeking to reverse that logic, with
coal for electricity being the residual product.'
Independent analysts believe opportunities are limited. 'I would be
surprised if half a dozen of the 20 were licensed off,' said one yesterday.
'Even that is optimistic.'
</TEXT>
