<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Auditors are told to provide more details of work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDITORS will be required to provide more detailed documentation of their
work under draft guidelines issued by the Auditing Practices Board.
Five new auditing standards call for formal documentation throughout the
audit process, and add new guidelines on making estimates.
Mr David Young, a member of the board, said: 'This represents a hardening of
emphasis on particular points. I think it will make a difference through
lots of minor individual changes.'
The guidelines reflect concerns by audit regulators that auditors do not
have adequate information on paper which can be inspected to determine the
quality of their work.
A standard on planning stresses more emphasis on documentation and a
distinction between formulating general strategy and detailed planning of
procedures.
One on documentation says there should be evidence that the audit was
carried out in accordance with auditing standards, and which gives detailed
information of the content of working papers during the audit.
A standard on estimates stresses the importance of the auditors verifying
with sufficient evidence the larger number of accounting estimates during an
audit.
Comments on the guidelines are invited by July 31.
The Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy yesterday unveiled
a new corporate image and announced fundamental changes to professional
qualifications.
New students will use open learning rather than being required to attend
college, making the qualification more flexible. Continuous assessment of
students' performance will assume a greater role. Greater emphasis is to be
placed on commercial accounting and reporting, taxation and business
planning.
Cipfa is also emphasising post-qualification development, and will shortly
launch an advanced diploma in business and financial management and a public
service Master of Business Administration degree.
The restructuring comes as Cipfa - which has about 11,500 members - faces
new challenges with the fundamental changes affecting the public sector.
Mr Noel Hepworth, director of the institute, said: 'Our objective is to
ensure that our qualifications and training remain relevant to the new
environment.'
The organisation has been given a new logo - the abbreviation Cipfa, with an
italic sweep to the letter p. It now calls itself 'the leading accountancy
body for the public services'.
</TEXT>
