<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Daf Vans sets turnover goal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEYLAND Daf Vans expects to achieve a turnover of about Pounds 150m in its
first year of operation, Mr Allan Amey, chief executive, said yesterday.
The company, which was acquired at the weekend through a management buy-out
from the Leyland Daf administrative receivers, is forecasting annual output
of about 12,000 vehicles compared with 20,099 last year. Mr Amey said the
contraction of the van operations and the shedding of more than half of its
workforce in receivership had reduced its break-even level to an output of
less than 10,000 vans a year.
The venture capital group 3i said yesterday that it had provided about
Pounds 6.5m of equity finance for the buy-out with an additional Pounds
500,000 coming from management and employees. It emerged yesterday that the
buy-out plan had run into serious difficulties last week, when at a late
stage Lloyds Development Capital withdrew its offer to provide Pounds 1.5m
in equity to the venture.
The Lloyds share was provided by 3i, which plans to seek other partners to
share part of its present risk.
The other main elements of the Leyland Daf Vans financial package include:
Working capital and a medium-term bank loan of more than Pounds 7m provided
by Royal Bank of Scotland.
Financing of up to Pounds 20m from United Dominions Trust, a subsidiary of
TSB Bank. UK state aid of Pounds 9m. The Department of Trade and Industry is
making regional selective assistance grants of Pounds 5m, while the
Department of the Environment has funded the Pounds 4m purchase by the
Birmingham Heartlands Development Corporation of 42 acres of surplus land at
the van plant site.
