<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Photos on bank cards cut fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EXPERIMENT in etching photographs and signatures on cheque guarantee
cards cut fraud by nearly 99 per cent, the Royal Bank of Scotland said
yesterday, John Gapper writes.
The bank, which has 1m customers, said it intended to be the first British
bank to offer them all the chance to have photographs on cards.
The laser etching of photographs and signatures on the reverse of the bank's
Highline cheque guarantee, cash dispenser and debit cards costs about Pounds
1.20 per card - about three times the cost of conventional cards.
The bank said an experiment covering 30,000 customers in 39 branches over
the past 18 months had reduced the anticipated level of fraud from about
Pounds 45,000 to three cases involving a total loss of Pounds 494.
The bank said it would not charge for such cards - though it charged
customers Pounds 2 per card in the pilot scheme. It believed it could
increase its gain by lowering the processing costs per card.
TSB has been testing putting photographs on customers' credit cards through
thermal imaging - a method adopted nationally by the National &amp; Provincial
Building society.
Mr Alex Barr, Royal Bank's card services development manager, said it was
also considering trying to put photographs on its credit cards. It would
have to negotiate this with First Data Resources, which makes its credit
cards.
</TEXT>
