<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Unitised policies questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACTUARIES HAVE expressed concern about the adequacy of reserves guaranteeing
the returns on certain life companies' unitised 'with-profits' policies.
A working party set up in 1991 by the actuarial professional bodies in
England and Scotland has confirmed that life assurance companies have been
rapidly switching 'with- profits' business to the unitised form first
introduced in the mid-1980s.
The working party's survey of 29 'mainstream' with-profits offices found
unitised with-profits reserves at the end of 1991 totalling Pounds 17.4bn -
21 per cent of all with-profits reserves.
The actuaries welcome the retention by the life offices of the right to
impose a 'market value adjuster' - a unit price reduction - in unusually
adverse investment conditions. But adjusters can prove controversial for
investors, who have little guidance on when they will be applied or how
large they might be.
Half the offices have imposed adjusters at some time on surrender of
policies, but not necessarily across the board; most appear to regard them
as a last resort. Half the companies have restrictions on their application,
and most offer guaranteed minimum annual returns. The working party says
some of these guarantees now look 'rather onerous'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
