<TEXT>
Prospects for rapid progress in South Africa's multi-party constitutional
talks appeared dim yesterday after several parties, led by the mainly Zulu
Inkatha Freedom Party, tried to delay the talks over procedural issues,
writes Patti Waldmeir in Johannesburg.
Yesterday's meeting ran into immediate problems as Inkatha and the
right-wing Conservative Party sought an adjournment. Inkatha opposes the
installation of a multi-party Transitional Executive Council by June, as
agreed by the government and the African National Congress.
