<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Nigeria cracks down on petrol smuggling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA yesterday banned all cross-border movements of petrol in an effort
to halt domestic fuel shortages and stop smuggling, Our Foreign Staff
writes.
The official petrol price in Nigeria is 0.7 naira a litre (about 1 1/2
pence), compared with N9.72 in Benin, N10.93 in Cameroon, N14.61 in Niger
and N16.11 in Chad.
Massive smuggling of petrol to these neighbouring states has left some parts
of Nigeria short of fuel. It also represents a substantial loss of revenue
for the government and the state-owned Nigerian National Petrolum
Corporation (NNPC). The government has said it plans to raise petrol prices
but has deferred implementing the decision, bitterly opposed by most
Nigerians, until after mid-June presidential elections.
</TEXT>
