<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / US calls for more cuts in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday said that further interest rates cuts were needed in Europe
to boost growth.
Mr Roger Altman, the US deputy Treasury secretary, said the US welcomed last
week's reduction in the Bundesbank's discount and Lombard rates. He said
that the recent pace of reductions in European interest rates was 'good'.
But it hoped that the process of lowering European interest rates would
continue.
Mr Altman made his comments to journalists at the annual meeting of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development after addressing the bank's
annual meeting.
His remarks suggested that that Germany could come under pressure from its
Group of Seven partners later this week to accelerate the easing of its
monetary policy. The G7 is due to meet on Thursday in Washington to discuss
the state of the world economy amid concern at the spread of recession to
Japan, Germany and other continental European countries.
Senior British Treasury officials said yesterday that the emergence of
recession to these parts of the world more than offset encouraging signs of
recovery in the US and the UK.
The officials also said the UK would press at this week's spring meetings of
the International Monetary Fund and World Bank for wage restraint in the
international financial institutions. The UK had been disappointed not to
win a majority on the IMF and World Bank boards to reduce this year's 6 per
cent pay increases at the two bodies.
