<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / France starts to emerge from economic doldrums
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER evidence emerged yesterday of the fledgling recovery in the French
economy when a survey of small and medium-sized businesses showed that some
companies are starting to hire extra staff and to increase investment.
Small companies have borne the brunt of France's economic problems over the
past year as high interest rates have cut into corporate investment and
consumer spending. Until recently the mood of small businesses was
unrelentingly grim. But a new survey by the Sofres research consultancy and
Credit du Nord bank published in yesterday's La Tribune Desfosses, suggests
confidence is slowly improving.
The number of small businesses intending to hire new staff rose to 8 per
cent, against 5 per cent three months ago. The proportion planning to lay
off employees has fallen from 44 per cent to 33 per cent over the same
period. Some 17 per cent of companies said they would raise investment.
The pressure on the French economy has alleviated slightly since the arrival
late last month of the new centre-right government and the subsequent falls
in interest rates.
