<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 93 / Bank to set up shop in east Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Bank for Reconstruction and Development will adopt a more
decentralised approach towards helping the former communist countries of
Europe and the former Soviet Union develop market economies, Mr Jacques
Attali, the EBRD president, said yesterday.
Reporting on a closed meeting of the EBRD board of governors, Mr Attali said
this was a turning point in the bank's operations. It is intended to make
its activities more visible and understandable in the countries in which it
operates.
Instead of taking all decisions from its London headquarters, the EBRD would
establish local institutions, most probably in partnership with governments
or private sector companies.
It is likely that the new philosophy will be applied in policies to help
create small and medium sized companies in the former communist states.
Two plans will be developed in the months ahead.
A Dollars 300m (Pounds 195m) fund to be administered by the EBRD, proposed
at the recent meeting of Group of Seven finance and foreign ministers in
Tokyo. This would take equity stakes in small and medium sized enterprises
in Russia.
A national development bank for Russia. Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance
minister and chairman of the EBRD board, suggested that this could be
modelled on the German Kreditanstalt fur Wiederaufbau that helped in the
reconstruction of West Germany after the second world war.
</TEXT>
