<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / Soros puts Dollars 400m into rising gold market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GEORGE Soros, the international currency trader, has agreed to buy a
Dollars 400m (Pounds 259m) stake in Newmont Mining, the Denver-based gold
mining company, as a way of gaining exposure to the rising gold market.
The company will announce today that funds controlled by the Soros family
have bought 6.8m shares in Newmont and agreed to buy a further 3.2m shares
at a cost of Dollars 39.50 a share. About 9m of the shares are being sold by
General Oriental Investment, which is controlled by Sir James Goldsmith,
with the rest coming from Lord Rothschild's RIT Capital Partners.
The sale will make Mr Soros the second largest shareholder in Newmont Mining
with 13 per cent, leaving Sir James with a stake of about 30 per cent. Lord
Rothschild's stake will fall from 7 to 5 per cent. Mr Soros rose to fame in
September when he made a Dollars 1bn profit as the UK was forced to leave
the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
Mr Gordon Parker, Newmont's chairman and president, said yesterday that he
'couldn't have imagined a better home for the shares, for what it tells the
world about sentiment on gold'.
The gold market has been improving recently with the price reaching a
six-month high of Dollars 347 per troy ounce on Friday.
'We're seeing the confluence of gold as a commodity and gold as money,' said
Mr Parker. Demand for gold from Asia has been increasing while production
has remained steady. At the same time, investors have increasingly been
buying gold as a hedge against uncertainty in the currency markets, fear of
inflation and economic unrest.
Newmont's shares rose by Dollars 3 in New York trading on Friday to Dollars
45 7/8 while trading in gold futures on the Comex was extremely busy.
Mr Parker said that Sir James's decision to sell part of his Newmont stake
was consistent with his plans when he bought into the company two and a half
years ago. Sir James first started selling Newmont shares in February when
he placed 1.8m with a range of institutions. At the time, he said he was
still bullish on gold.
Sir James acquired a 42 per cent holding in Newmont as part of a deal with
Lord Hanson in October 1990.
</TEXT>
