<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 93 / Portillo expects modest recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is heading for an economic recovery which will be modest compared
with that of the 1980s but should be better sustained, Mr Michael Portillo,
chief secretary to the Treasury, said yesterday.
Provisional first-quarter figures for gross domestic product to be published
today are generally expected to signal a formal end to the recession.
Mr Portillo said it was likely that rates of growth 'even a few years out'
would not be as fast as in the 1980s, but that they would be 'better
sustained, for a longer period of time and with greater certainty'.
He said recent data on industrial production, retail sales, exports and from
the housing market were 'very encouraging' while, contrary to expectations,
there had been falls in unemployment.
The government was confident that it would meet its goal of holding
underlying inflation in the 1 per cent to 4 per cent target range this year
and next.
Mr Portillo, in an interview on BBC Radio's World this Weekend programme,
promised the government would adjust its policies to keep inflation under
control. Although 'there was no immediate prospect' of the UK rejoining the
European exchange rate mechanism, the government would take account of the
sterling exchange rate in pursuing its goal of low inflation.
Mr Portillo rejected suggestions that Britain's manufacturing industry had
been so weakened by the recession that the country faced another cycle of
stop-go.
'I don't know that this recovery is going to be like other recoveries,' he
said. He pointed out that UK manufacturing productivity and exports had
never been higher. Because industry had kept control of wages, unit wage
costs were falling, giving the British economy a lasting efficiency and
competitive gain that was 'over and above' that conferred by the fall in the
value of sterling since last September.
Falling unit wage costs might already have contributed to surprise falls in
unemployment in February and March. He urged managers, trade unions and
opposition parties to support further wage restraint.
Mr Portillo also sounded an optimistic note about UK export prospects in
spite of the worsening economic condition of Britain's main European
markets. The government has passed a turning point in its fortunes, Sir
Norman Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, said yesterday. 'The fact of
the matter is that the recovery has been taking place over the last 12
months, but it has now speeded up,' he said on the BBC TV Breakfast with
Frost programme.
</TEXT>
